Pour the @water{240%ml} and the @vegetable stock paste{1} into a #saucepan{} and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @bulgur wheat{120%g}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for ~{1%minute}. Pop a lid on the #pan{} and remove from the heat.

Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, trim the @courgette{1}, then quarter lengthways. Chop into 1cm chunks.

Drain the @king prawns{300%g}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the courgette. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

Fry, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Once the courgette has softened, add the prawns and @ras-el-hanout{1/2%tsp} (add less if you'd prefer things milder) to the pan.

Mix well and season with salt and pepper.

Cook, stirring occasionally, until the prawns are cooked, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Meanwhile, crumble the @greek style salad cheese{50%g} into small pieces.

When your bulgur wheat is ready, fluff it up with a #fork{} and stir through the @zhoug style paste{50g} (add less if you'd prefer things milder).

Add the cooked prawns and courgette to the bulgur and gently mix together. Taste and season with salt and pepper if needed.

Share the zhoug bulgur and ras-el-hanout prawns between your #bowls{}.

Spoon over the @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g} and scatter the greek style salad cheese over the top to finish.

Enjoy!